    • load

      public static Module load(String modelPath, int loadMode)
      Loads a serialized ExecuTorch module from the specified path on the disk.
      Parameters:
      modelPath - path to file that contains the serialized ExecuTorch module.
      loadMode - load mode for the module. See constants in Module.
      Returns:
      new Module object which owns the model module.

    • forward

      public EValue[] forward(EValue... inputs)
      Runs the 'forward' method of this module with the specified arguments.
      Parameters:
      inputs - arguments for the ExecuTorch module's 'forward' method. Note: if method 'forward' requires inputs but no inputs are given, the function will not error out, but run 'forward' with sample inputs.
      Returns:
      return value from the 'forward' method.

    • execute

      public EValue[] execute(String methodName, EValue... inputs)
      Runs the specified method of this module with the specified arguments.
      Parameters:
      methodName - name of the ExecuTorch method to run.
      inputs - arguments that will be passed to ExecuTorch method.
      Returns:
      return value from the method.

    • loadMethod

      public int loadMethod(String methodName)
      Load a method on this module. This might help with the first time inference performance, because otherwise the method is loaded lazily when it's execute. Note: this function is synchronous, and will block until the method is loaded. Therefore, it is recommended to call this on a background thread. However, users need to make sure that they don't execute before this function returns.
      Returns:
      the Error code if there was an error loading the method

    • readLogBuffer

      public String[] readLogBuffer()
      Retrieve the in-memory log buffer, containing the most recent ExecuTorch log entries.

    • destroy

      public void destroy()
      Explicitly destroys the native torch::jit::Module. Calling this method is not required, as the native object will be destroyed when this object is garbage-collected. However, the timing of garbage collection is not guaranteed, so proactively calling destroy can free memory more quickly. See HybridData.resetNative().
